<subSubSection id="AD7CEE339A4631D052CBCD411587C9F4" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="03BAC98A1EAABC1113C6FF885A4C19F1" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="659AA5CA1A3BC6AE37DC322EAB6BFD5D" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">Body fusiform, dorso-ventrally flattened. Gnathosoma short, downwardly curved, cheliceral stylet short; prodorsal shield small and sickle-shaped; scapular tubercles and scapular setae sc lacking; pedipalp genual setae d present and simple; coxae without setae 1b; femoral setae bv of leg I present; genual setae lâ€³ of leg II present; empodium simple; female genitalia appressed to the coxae, genital cover flap smooth, triangular, located between coxae II; apodeme normal in length.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="51677ACF64AC647CE868C231C04CBD6E" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" type="type species">
<paragraph id="C738378326062C7500F8F51D8DF86AE5" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">Type species.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FF31F08AD079F289D10CA0BE4A075681" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">
<taxonomicName id="6BF0584975A88AF8FC7C72B1437ED28D" authority="Mohanasundaram, 1985" authorityName="Mohanasundaram" authorityYear="1985" class="Arachnida" family="Eriophyidae" genus="Ashieldophyes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ashieldophyes glochidionae" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="glochidionae">Ashieldophyes glochidionae</taxonomicName>
Chakrabarti &amp; Pandit, 2009.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="138A8F534103D4D4F33DE97CD95169CD" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">The genus is monotypic.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C47A738244545226D3C83BB07392B380" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="1689BBE592944C809E397FA9316D577D" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D008B5F470405750E6C80CD0C85EB3F9" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">Brevi derived from the adjective Latin word brevis meaning short (in relation to prodorsal shield) and ophyes derived from eriophyes meaning erion = wool + phyes = a grower/maker.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
